               <birth when="1860"/>
               <floruit notBefore="1886" notAfter="1924">He was a Protestant educated traditional Ethiopian scholar. In <date>1886</date>,  he became a member of the Bethel 
                  congregation in <placeName ref="LOC2852Emkull">ʾƎmkullu</placeName> and was employed by the mission in translation and teaching work. 
                  In <date>1905</date>, <persName ref="PRS9347TayyaGa">Tāyya Gabra Māryām</persName> left 
                  <placeName ref="LOC3010Ethiop">Ethiopia</placeName> to <placeName ref="Q64">Berlin</placeName> where he stayed there as 
                  a visiting scholar, acting as a resource person and co-worker to <persName ref="PRS7124Mittwoch">Mittwoch</persName>. 
                  After he returned  from <placeName ref="Q64">Berlin</placeName> in <date>1908</date>, he faced  opposition due to his religious views. 
                  But he enjoyed a peaceful years under the reigns of <persName ref="PRS5620IyasuV">ʾIyāsu (V)</persName> and 
                  <persName ref="PRS10671Zawditu">Zawditu</persName>. He authored most of his works including his famous work, 
                  <title ref="LIT1603Histor">History of the people of Ethiopia</title> during those years. </floruit>
               <death when="1924"/>
